Note:
==============================================================================
PARALLEL IMPORT PROCESSING SYSTEM v0.0.8.5  (P2-C #117-aware rewrite)
==============================================================================

This module drives multi-threaded import resolution against the real #117
platform threading API exposed by
  compiler/frontend/primitives/assembly/threading.runa.

The previous incarnation of this file imported the non-existent
`compiler/frontend/primitives/threading/posix_threads.runa` module and called
sixteen fictional `pthread_*` / `atomic_counter_*` / `get_nproc` symbols that
never resolved. The whole subsystem was dead weight: the object file
compiled in isolation but never linked, so the moment a build wired up real
multi-worker parsing the link broke. This rewrite eliminates that failure
mode end-to-end.

Architectural highlights:
  * Per-worker arenas (Resolution A from DEV-LOG #117 sec5): each worker
    parses into its own arena. No shared-arena race on the bump pointer.
    Arenas are created on the main thread before workers spawn and destroyed
    on shutdown after the deterministic merge phase has consumed their AST
    nodes. Worker arenas live for the lifetime of the import context
    (matches serial-path semantics: serial imports' AST also lives until
    end-of-compilation).
  * Monitor pattern (mutex + condvar) for the work queue. Producers
    (main thread) and consumers (worker pool) coordinate through a single
    queue_mutex. Workers wait on work_cv when the queue is empty; main
    waits on done_cv until the completion counter reaches expected.
  * Lock-free completion counter. atomic_increment under release semantics
    is published every time a worker finishes a task. Main reads it under
    queue_mutex (the cv contract) and waits on done_cv otherwise.
  * Ring-buffer work queue with monotonic head/tail and modulo-capacity
    index. The previous implementation incremented tail without wrapping;
    the queue therefore grew unbounded. This rewrite preserves enqueue
    order across resizes by re-packing into a linear layout.
  * Deterministic merge. After every worker has joined, the main thread
    iterates tasks in enqueue_order and merges results into main_program.
    No shared writes from worker threads.
  * Graceful degradation. platform_threading_available() returns 0 on any
    backend P2-B has not verified. process_imports_parallel returns a
    sentinel (2) on that path, and the driver falls back to
    process_imports_recursive.
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as MemoryCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/atomic_core.runa" as Atomic
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/assembly/threading.runa" as Threading
Import "compiler/frontend/lexical/lexer.runa" as Lexer
Import "compiler/frontend/parsing/parser.runa" as Parser
Import "compiler/frontend/import_system/core.runa" as ImportCore
Import "compiler/frontend/import_system/resolution.runa" as Resolution
Import "runtime/core/memory/arena.runa" as Arena

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Module Constants
Note: ============================================================================

Constant WORKER_ARENA_CAPACITY as Integer is 1048576
Note: Default per-worker arena size (1 MiB). arena_create will grow as needed;
Note: this is the starting page count to keep the first batch of parses
Note: allocation-failure-free without wasting RSS on small builds.

Constant DEFAULT_QUEUE_CAPACITY as Integer is 64
Note: Initial work-queue ring-buffer capacity. enqueue_task doubles this
Note: on overflow, preserving enqueue_order across the resize by re-packing
Note: pending tasks into a linear layout starting at head = 0.

Constant POOL_STRUCT_SIZE as Integer is 72
Constant WORKER_SLOT_SIZE as Integer is 40
Constant QUEUE_STRUCT_SIZE as Integer is 56
Constant TASK_STRUCT_SIZE as Integer is 56
Constant WORKER_CONTEXT_SIZE as Integer is 32
Constant CELL_SIZE as Integer is 8

Note: ThreadPool field offsets (POOL_STRUCT_SIZE bytes):
Note:   0  workers_array        ptr to N * WORKER_SLOT_SIZE bytes
Note:   8  worker_count         N
Note:  16  work_queue           ptr to WorkQueue
Note:  24  queue_mutex          handle from platform_mutex_create
Note:  32  work_cv              handle from platform_condvar_create
Note:  40  done_cv              handle from platform_condvar_create
Note:  48  completion_counter   ptr to 8-byte atomic cell
Note:  56  shutdown_flag        ptr to 8-byte atomic cell
Note:  64  threading_available  1 = threads work, 0 = serial-fallback

Note: WorkerSlot field offsets (WORKER_SLOT_SIZE bytes):
Note:   0  thread_handle        handle returned by platform_thread_create
Note:   8  worker_id            ordinal 0..N-1
Note:  16  worker_arena         per-worker arena (arena_create result)
Note:  24  pool_ptr             back-pointer to ThreadPool
Note:  32  state                0=idle, 1=busy, 2=exited

Note: WorkQueue field offsets (QUEUE_STRUCT_SIZE bytes):
Note:   0  tasks_array          ptr to capacity * 8 bytes
Note:   8  task_count           pending tasks
Note:  16  head                 monotonic dequeue cursor
Note:  24  tail                 monotonic enqueue cursor
Note:  32  capacity             ring-buffer modulo
Note:  40  total_enqueued       cumulative enqueues (stats)
Note:  48  total_dequeued       cumulative dequeues (stats)

Note: ImportTask field offsets (TASK_STRUCT_SIZE bytes):
Note:   0  import_path          ptr to import path string (main arena)
Note:   8  enqueue_order        i in 0..import_count
Note:  16  assigned_worker      worker id that processed this (-1 = unprocessed)
Note:  24  parsed_program       ptr to parsed AST (0 on failure)
Note:  32  error_code           0=success, 1-6=phase-specific failure
Note:  40  worker_arena_ptr     arena that owns parsed_program (for lifetime)
Note:  48  resolved_path        ptr to resolved path (worker arena)

Note: WorkerContext field offsets (WORKER_CONTEXT_SIZE bytes):
Note:   0  worker_id
Note:   8  pool_ptr
Note:  16  worker_arena
Note:  24  main_context

Note: ImportContext slots used by parallel.runa:
Note:    64  parallel_workers   read-only, configured by driver
Note:   200  thread_pool        ptr to our ThreadPool (we own this slot)
Note:   208  work_queue         ptr to WorkQueue (mirrored from pool for fast access)
Note:   216  sync_primitives    legacy slot, retained as 0 (we no longer indirect)

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Work Queue Primitives (single-threaded; caller must hold queue_mutex)
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "initialize_work_queue" that takes main_arena as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    @Reasoning
    Allocate the WorkQueue control block and its initial tasks_array. Both
    live in the main arena because the queue's lifetime equals the thread
    pool's lifetime, which equals the import context's lifetime.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    The ring buffer uses monotonic head/tail counters with modulo-capacity
    indexing. The previous implementation grew the array unboundedly because
    enqueue did `tail = tail + 1` without wrapping; this version starts with
    a fixed capacity and only resizes when task_count >= capacity.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Arena allocation is O(1) bump-pointer. DEFAULT_QUEUE_CAPACITY is sized
    to amortize resize cost for typical import counts (8-256 imports per
    program) without wasting memory on tiny programs. The zero-init writes
    of the seven control fields are cache-line-friendly: they touch a single
    64-byte line.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    No untrusted input flows into this Process. The arena pointer is
    compiler-owned. Allocation failure (0 return from arena_allocate) is
    propagated to the caller; no partial state escapes - if either
    allocation fails the queue pointer is dropped on the floor (arena
    reclaims it at end of compilation) and we return 0.
    @End Security_Scope
    :End Note

    Let queue be proc arena_allocate from Arena with main_arena, QUEUE_STRUCT_SIZE
    If queue is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let initial_array_size be DEFAULT_QUEUE_CAPACITY multiplied by CELL_SIZE
    Let tasks_array be proc arena_allocate from Arena with main_arena, initial_array_size
    If tasks_array is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with queue, 0, tasks_array
    proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with queue, 8, 0
    proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with queue, 16, 0
    proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with queue, 24, 0
    proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with queue, 32, DEFAULT_QUEUE_CAPACITY
    proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with queue, 40, 0
    proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with queue, 48, 0

    Return queue
End Process

Process called "resize_work_queue" that takes work_queue as Integer, new_capacity as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    @Reasoning
    The ring buffer must grow when task_count reaches capacity, because
    further enqueues would overwrite live entries. Resizing in-place
    preserves the queue invariants (head/tail/task_count) and keeps the
    caller's queue pointer stable so worker threads do not need to
    re-resolve the queue address. We linearize the layout during copy so
    the post-resize state is identical to a freshly-initialized queue with
    task_count entries already enqueued.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Grow the ring buffer in-place, preserving task_count pending tasks in
    their original enqueue order. We allocate a fresh linear array sized to
    `new_capacity * 8` and copy the pending region starting at head%cap, in
    up to two segments depending on whether the live region wraps the old
    array. After the copy, head is reset to 0 and tail to task_count so the
    queue resumes from a clean linear layout.
    The caller MUST hold queue_mutex during this operation.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Resize is O(task_count) due to the copy loop. The geometric growth
    policy in enqueue_task (capacity * 2) amortizes resize cost to O(1) per
    enqueue across the lifetime of the queue. The zero-fill loop on the new
    array prevents stale-pointer hazards if a future dequeue ever indexes
    past task_count due to a logic bug; this is defensive but cheap because
    the working set fits in L1 for typical capacities.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    The work_queue pointer is compiler-owned; new_capacity is computed by
    enqueue_task (capacity * 2, bounded by import_count * 2). No untrusted
    input. We carefully distinguish arena-owned from heap-owned old arrays:
    deallocating an arena-owned pointer would corrupt the layout allocator
    (see ownership comment in body). The capacity-check guard is the safety
    barrier for that boundary.
    @End Security_Scope
    :End Note

    Let old_array be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with work_queue, 0
    Let task_count be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with work_queue, 8
    Let head be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with work_queue, 16
    Let old_capacity be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with work_queue, 32

    Let new_array_bytes be new_capacity multiplied by CELL_SIZE
    Let new_array be proc allocate from Layout with new_array_bytes
    If new_array is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Zero new array so unused slots don't look like ghost tasks.
    Let zero_idx be 0
    While zero_idx is less than new_capacity:
        Let zero_offset be zero_idx multiplied by CELL_SIZE
        proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with new_array, zero_offset, 0
        Set zero_idx to zero_idx plus 1
    End While

    Note: Copy task_count tasks from old_array starting at head%old_capacity.
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than task_count:
        Let src_idx be head plus i
        Let src_mod be src_idx modulo by old_capacity
        Let src_offset be src_mod multiplied by CELL_SIZE
        Let task_ptr be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with old_array, src_offset
        Let dst_offset be i multiplied by CELL_SIZE
        proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with new_array, dst_offset, task_ptr
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with work_queue, 0, new_array
    proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with work_queue, 16, 0
    proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with work_queue, 24, task_count
    proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with work_queue, 32, new_capacity

    Note: Only deallocate the old array if it was previously allocated by
    Note: this resize path. The initial array is arena-owned; calling
    Note: deallocate on it would corrupt the layout allocator. We detect
    Note: arena ownership by checking whether old_capacity equals the
    Note: default initial capacity: the first resize replaces an arena
    Note: array with a heap array, all subsequent resizes replace heap
    Note: arrays.
    If old_capacity is not equal to DEFAULT_QUEUE_CAPACITY:
        If old_array is not equal to 0:
            proc deallocate from Layout with old_array
        End If
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "enqueue_task" that takes work_queue as Integer, task as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    @Reasoning
    Producer side of the SPMC monitor. The main thread is the sole
    producer (enqueueing all imports up-front before workers begin
    consuming concurrently); the mutex still serializes enqueue against
    worker dequeues. Doubling capacity on overflow rather than panicking
    keeps the queue correct even if the upstream import-count estimate is
    low.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Append a task at tail%capacity. If the buffer is full, double capacity
    via resize_work_queue first. tail is monotonic; only the modulo index
    wraps. Caller MUST hold queue_mutex.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Hot path is a single memory_set_qword at the tail slot plus three
    counter updates (tail, task_count, total_enqueued) - amortized O(1).
    Resize overhead is geometric, so total enqueue cost over a session is
    O(n) for n tasks. total_enqueued is a diagnostic counter; removing it
    would save one cache write per enqueue if profiling demands it.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    The task pointer is compiler-owned (allocated by create_import_task
    from the main arena). We do not validate it; storing 0 is permitted
    and dequeue_task treats it as empty-queue. The caller invariant
    (queue_mutex held) is what prevents tearing of the tail/task_count
    pair, not any local check.
    @End Security_Scope
    :End Note

    Let task_count be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with work_queue, 8
    Let capacity be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with work_queue, 32

    If task_count is greater than or equal to capacity:
        Let new_capacity be capacity multiplied by 2
        If new_capacity is less than DEFAULT_QUEUE_CAPACITY:
            Set new_capacity to DEFAULT_QUEUE_CAPACITY
        End If
        Let resize_ok be proc resize_work_queue with work_queue, new_capacity
        If resize_ok is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        Set capacity to new_capacity
        Set task_count to proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with work_queue, 8
    End If

    Let tasks_array be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with work_queue, 0
    Let tail be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with work_queue, 24
    Let slot_index be tail modulo by capacity
    Let slot_offset be slot_index multiplied by CELL_SIZE

    proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with tasks_array, slot_offset, task

    Let new_tail be tail plus 1
    Let new_count be task_count plus 1
    Let total_enq be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with work_queue, 40
    proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with work_queue, 24, new_tail
    proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with work_queue, 8, new_count
    proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with work_queue, 40, total_enq plus 1

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "dequeue_task" that takes work_queue as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    @Reasoning
    Consumer side of the SPMC monitor. Returning 0 on empty rather than
    blocking is intentional: the worker loop owns the wait-on-condition
    decision so it can also test the shutdown flag in the same critical
    section. Decoupling those two concerns would force an extra mutex
    cycle per wakeup.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Pop the head task. Returns 0 if the queue is empty; otherwise the task
    pointer. Caller MUST hold queue_mutex.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Hot path is a single memory_get_qword at the head slot plus three
    counter updates - amortized O(1). The empty-queue early return avoids
    touching the tasks_array entirely when the queue is drained, keeping
    the worker-spin cost minimal between wakeups.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    No untrusted input. The returned task pointer is compiler-owned. The
    caller-holds-mutex invariant prevents two workers from observing the
    same head value and dequeueing the same task twice.
    @End Security_Scope
    :End Note

    Let task_count be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with work_queue, 8
    If task_count is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let tasks_array be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with work_queue, 0
    Let head be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with work_queue, 16
    Let capacity be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with work_queue, 32
    Let slot_index be head modulo by capacity
    Let slot_offset be slot_index multiplied by CELL_SIZE
    Let task be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with tasks_array, slot_offset

    Let new_head be head plus 1
    Let new_count be task_count minus 1
    Let total_deq be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with work_queue, 48
    proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with work_queue, 16, new_head
    proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with work_queue, 8, new_count
    proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with work_queue, 48, total_deq plus 1

    Return task
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: ImportTask Construction
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "create_import_task" that takes import_path as Integer, enqueue_order as Integer, main_arena as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    @Reasoning
    All tasks are allocated up front from the main arena, sized exactly to
    import_count. Workers fill in resolved_path / parsed_program /
    worker_arena_ptr / error_code; they never resize the task struct.
    Fixed layout means workers can write into a task slot without locking;
    the main thread guarantees no aliasing because each task is only
    enqueued once.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Allocate TASK_STRUCT_SIZE bytes from main_arena. Initialize the seven
    qword fields at offsets 0/8/16/24/32/40/48: import_path, enqueue_order,
    -1 (sentinel worker_id meaning "not yet picked up"), 0 (parsed_program
    placeholder), 0 (worker_arena_ptr placeholder), 0 (error_code = no
    error), and 0 (resolved_path placeholder filled in by worker).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Arena bump-pointer allocation: O(1). Seven sequential qword writes hit
    one cache line. Allocation cost dominates the rest of the task
    lifecycle's pre-work, so reducing TASK_STRUCT_SIZE below 56 bytes
    would not yield measurable wins.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    import_path is a String pointer derived from the program's import
    AST; its provenance is parser output, not external input directly.
    Path validation/sandbox enforcement happens later inside
    resolve_module_path on the worker thread. We do not dereference
    import_path here; we only store the pointer.
    @End Security_Scope
    :End Note

    Let task be proc arena_allocate from Arena with main_arena, TASK_STRUCT_SIZE
    If task is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with task, 0, import_path
    proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with task, 8, enqueue_order
    proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with task, 16, -1
    proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with task, 24, 0
    proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with task, 32, 0
    proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with task, 40, 0
    proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with task, 48, 0

    Return task
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Worker Task Processing
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "process_import_task" that takes task as Integer, worker_slot as Integer, main_context as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    @Reasoning
    Run the full resolve -> read -> lex -> parse pipeline for a single
    import task on a worker thread. All allocations route through the
    worker's own arena (worker_slot+16), never the shared main arena.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Five-phase staged pipeline with per-phase error codes (1=resolve,
    2=read, 3=lex, 4=parser_create, 5=parse). Each phase writes its
    failure code into task[32] and returns 1 (worker reported error,
    keep running). Success records the parsed program at task[24] and
    the owning worker arena at task[40] so the merge phase can locate
    the AST nodes after join. Resources (lexer, parser, source buffer)
    are destroyed in reverse-creation order on both success and failure.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    The hot path is the parser_parse_program call which dominates wall
    time per import. Per-worker arenas eliminate allocator contention
    across workers; the only synchronization in this Process is the
    error-code write at the end, which the main thread reads only
    AFTER join.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    The import path is validated by Resolution.resolve_module_path BEFORE
    any file I/O happens; that resolver enforces the security_flags policy
    set on main_context (sandbox roots, allow-list, no traversal, etc.).
    The worker never touches the filesystem with an unresolved string.
    @End Security_Scope
    :End Note

    Let worker_id be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with worker_slot, 8
    Let worker_arena be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with worker_slot, 16

    proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with task, 16, worker_id

    Let import_path be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with task, 0
    If import_path is equal to 0:
        proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with task, 32, 1
        Return 1
    End If

    Let resolved_path be proc resolve_module_path from Resolution with import_path, main_context, worker_arena
    If resolved_path is equal to 0:
        proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with task, 32, 1
        Return 1
    End If
    proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with task, 48, resolved_path

    Let import_source be proc read_file_internal from ImportCore with resolved_path
    If import_source is equal to 0:
        proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with task, 32, 2
        Return 1
    End If

    Let source_length be proc string_length from StringCore with import_source
    Let import_lexer be proc lexer_create from Lexer with import_source, source_length, 0, worker_arena
    If import_lexer is equal to 0:
        proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with task, 32, 3
        proc deallocate from Layout with import_source
        Return 1
    End If

    Let import_parser be proc parser_create from Parser with import_lexer, worker_arena
    If import_parser is equal to 0:
        proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with task, 32, 4
        proc lexer_destroy from Lexer with import_lexer
        proc deallocate from Layout with import_source
        Return 1
    End If

    Let import_program be proc parser_parse_program from Parser with import_parser
    If import_program is equal to 0:
        proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with task, 32, 5
        proc parser_destroy from Parser with import_parser
        proc lexer_destroy from Lexer with import_lexer
        proc deallocate from Layout with import_source
        Return 1
    End If

    proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with task, 24, import_program
    proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with task, 40, worker_arena
    proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with task, 32, 0

    proc parser_destroy from Parser with import_parser
    proc lexer_destroy from Lexer with import_lexer
    proc deallocate from Layout with import_source

    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Worker Main Loop
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "worker_main" that takes worker_context as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    @Reasoning
    Standard monitor-pattern consumer. Hold queue_mutex while inspecting
    the queue; if empty, check the shutdown flag with atomic_load_acquire
    and either exit (clean teardown via platform_thread_exit) or wait on
    work_cv. After dequeueing, release the mutex BEFORE running the parse
    so other workers can dequeue concurrently. On task completion,
    atomic_increment the completion counter (release semantics built into
    seq_cst atomics) and signal done_cv so the main thread observes
    progress.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Read the six pool fields (workers_array, work_queue, queue_mutex,
    work_cv, done_cv, completion_counter, shutdown_flag) once at entry to
    keep the hot loop register-resident. Per-iteration: lock mutex, spin
    on dequeue+shutdown-check+condvar_wait until task obtained or
    shutdown observed, unlock mutex, set worker_state=1 (working), run
    process_import_task, increment completion counter, signal done_cv,
    reset worker_state=0. On shutdown observed: set worker_state=2
    (exited) and call platform_thread_exit so the kernel can reap the
    TID at join time.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    The mutex is held ONLY for queue inspection and dequeue, NOT during
    the parse phase - this is the key concurrency win versus a naive
    serialize-everything implementation. atomic_increment uses
    architecture-native fetch-add (lock xadd on x86_64), faster than a
    mutex-protected counter. The condvar wakeup pattern (signal on
    enqueue, broadcast on shutdown) avoids the thundering herd while
    workers are draining the queue.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    The worker_context pointer is compiler-owned (allocated by
    create_worker_context from the main arena). All five reads from
    worker_context use known fixed offsets. The mutex/condvar handles
    are obtained from pool, also compiler-owned. The only external
    surface in this Process is the eventual call to process_import_task,
    whose own annotation covers the per-import security boundary.
    @End Security_Scope
    :End Note

    Let worker_id be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with worker_context, 0
    Let pool be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with worker_context, 8
    Let worker_arena be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with worker_context, 16
    Let main_context be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with worker_context, 24

    Let workers_array be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with pool, 0
    Let worker_slot_offset be worker_id multiplied by WORKER_SLOT_SIZE
    Let worker_slot be workers_array plus worker_slot_offset

    Let work_queue be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with pool, 16
    Let queue_mutex be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with pool, 24
    Let work_cv be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with pool, 32
    Let done_cv be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with pool, 40
    Let completion_counter be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with pool, 48
    Let shutdown_flag be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with pool, 56

    Let keep_running be 1
    While keep_running is equal to 1:
        proc platform_mutex_lock from Threading with queue_mutex

        Let task be proc dequeue_task with work_queue
        While task is equal to 0:
            Let shutdown_state be proc atomic_load_acquire from Atomic with shutdown_flag
            If shutdown_state is equal to 1:
                proc platform_mutex_unlock from Threading with queue_mutex
                proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with worker_slot, 32, 2
                proc platform_thread_exit from Threading with 0
                Return 0
            End If
            proc platform_condvar_wait from Threading with work_cv, queue_mutex
            Set task to proc dequeue_task with work_queue
        End While

        proc platform_mutex_unlock from Threading with queue_mutex

        proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with worker_slot, 32, 1

        proc process_import_task with task, worker_slot, main_context

        proc atomic_increment from Atomic with completion_counter
        proc platform_condvar_signal from Threading with done_cv

        proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with worker_slot, 32, 0
    End While

    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Worker Spawn / Cleanup
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "create_worker_context" that takes worker_id as Integer, pool as Integer, worker_arena as Integer, main_context as Integer, main_arena as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    @Reasoning
    Build the four-field context struct passed by-pointer to worker_main
    as its sole argument. The struct contents are immutable for the
    worker's lifetime, so they can be read without synchronization. Living
    in the main arena means the context survives until end-of-compilation,
    matching the worker thread's join-then-arena-destroy lifecycle.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Allocate WORKER_CONTEXT_SIZE bytes from main_arena, then write the
    four qword fields at offsets 0/8/16/24: worker_id, pool pointer,
    worker_arena pointer (the per-worker arena used for parse output),
    and main_context (used for resolve_module_path policy lookups).
    Return the struct pointer.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Arena bump-pointer allocation: O(1). Four sequential qword writes hit
    one cache line. The context is read once per worker boot then is
    cold for the rest of the worker's life.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    All five arguments are compiler-owned pointers/integers. No untrusted
    input. The worker_arena passed in here becomes the allocation root
    for all per-task work; if it were swapped to point at the shared
    main_arena, all per-worker isolation would collapse. The caller
    (create_worker_thread) is the sole site that constructs this arena
    via arena_create.
    @End Security_Scope
    :End Note

    Let worker_ctx be proc arena_allocate from Arena with main_arena, WORKER_CONTEXT_SIZE
    If worker_ctx is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with worker_ctx, 0, worker_id
    proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with worker_ctx, 8, pool
    proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with worker_ctx, 16, worker_arena
    proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with worker_ctx, 24, main_context

    Return worker_ctx
End Process

Process called "create_worker_thread" that takes worker_id as Integer, pool as Integer, workers_array as Integer, main_context as Integer, main_arena as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    @Reasoning
    Spawn one worker: allocate its arena, initialize its slot in the
    pool's workers_array, build its context, then call
    platform_thread_create to start the OS thread. Doing all four steps
    atomically per worker (rather than batching) means a partial-failure
    cleanup path is simple: if any step fails the caller
    (create_worker_threads) has a coherent state to roll back from.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Compute the slot pointer (workers_array + worker_id * WORKER_SLOT_SIZE).
    Create the per-worker arena via arena_create with WORKER_ARENA_CAPACITY
    (mmap-backed, independent of the main arena). Initialize the five
    qword slot fields at offsets 0/8/16/24/32: handle=0 (filled after
    thread_create), worker_id, worker_arena, pool, worker_state=0 (idle).
    Build the worker context via create_worker_context. If either context
    or thread creation fails, destroy the arena and clear the slot
    fields before returning 0.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Worker spawn is amortized once per parallel session; not on the hot
    path. arena_create is the dominant cost (one mmap syscall plus a
    small header init); platform_thread_create costs one clone() syscall.
    The slot field writes use known compile-time offsets so the codegen
    folds them to direct memory stores with no indirection.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    All five arguments are compiler-owned. The platform_thread_create
    call passes worker_main (a code pointer) and worker_ctx (a data
    pointer) - both compiler-controlled, no possibility of confused
    deputy. If platform_thread_create returns <= 0 we treat it as failure
    and roll back; we never store a negative handle into the slot.
    @End Security_Scope
    :End Note

    Let slot_offset be worker_id multiplied by WORKER_SLOT_SIZE
    Let worker_slot be workers_array plus slot_offset

    Let worker_arena be proc arena_create from Arena with WORKER_ARENA_CAPACITY
    If worker_arena is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with worker_slot, 0, 0
    proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with worker_slot, 8, worker_id
    proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with worker_slot, 16, worker_arena
    proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with worker_slot, 24, pool
    proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with worker_slot, 32, 0

    Let worker_ctx be proc create_worker_context with worker_id, pool, worker_arena, main_context, main_arena
    If worker_ctx is equal to 0:
        proc arena_destroy from Arena with worker_arena
        proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with worker_slot, 16, 0
        Return 0
    End If

    Let handle be proc platform_thread_create from Threading with worker_main, worker_ctx
    If handle is less than or equal to 0:
        proc arena_destroy from Arena with worker_arena
        proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with worker_slot, 16, 0
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with worker_slot, 0, handle
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "create_worker_threads" that takes worker_count as Integer, pool as Integer, main_context as Integer, main_arena as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    @Reasoning
    Allocate the workers_array (worker_count contiguous slots, each
    WORKER_SLOT_SIZE bytes) then spawn worker_count threads in sequence.
    On any spawn failure, signal already-spawned workers to exit, join
    them, and destroy their arenas via cleanup_worker_threads; this
    leaves the system in a clean state where the caller can fall back to
    serial without leaking threads or arenas.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    arena_allocate workers_array (worker_count * WORKER_SLOT_SIZE bytes).
    Zero-init the array byte-by-byte so every slot field starts at 0
    (handle, worker_id, worker_arena, pool, worker_state). Loop spawn_idx
    from 0 to worker_count-1 calling create_worker_thread for each. If
    any spawn returns 0, call cleanup_worker_threads with the already-
    spawned subset (spawn_idx) and return 0. On success, return the
    workers_array pointer for the caller to store in the pool struct.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Sequential spawn rather than barrier-style fan-out: simpler, and the
    spawn cost is dominated by the kernel clone() syscall which is
    inherently serial in glibc. For worker_count <= 16 the total spawn
    time is sub-millisecond. The byte-level zero-init loop could be
    coalesced to qword writes but the savings are negligible for
    typical worker_counts (4-8).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    All four arguments are compiler-owned. worker_count is sized from
    platform_hardware_concurrency and clamped to a sane range upstream
    in initialize_thread_pool. If allocation of workers_array fails we
    return 0 immediately without spawning anything; partial-failure
    cleanup is handled by cleanup_worker_threads which validates each
    slot field before acting on it.
    @End Security_Scope
    :End Note

    Let array_bytes be worker_count multiplied by WORKER_SLOT_SIZE
    Let workers_array be proc arena_allocate from Arena with main_arena, array_bytes
    If workers_array is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than array_bytes:
        proc memory_set_byte from MemoryCore with workers_array, i, 0
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Let spawn_idx be 0
    While spawn_idx is less than worker_count:
        Let ok be proc create_worker_thread with spawn_idx, pool, workers_array, main_context, main_arena
        If ok is equal to 0:
            proc cleanup_worker_threads with workers_array, spawn_idx, pool
            Return 0
        End If
        Set spawn_idx to spawn_idx plus 1
    End While

    Return workers_array
End Process

Process called "cleanup_worker_threads" that takes workers_array as Integer, count as Integer, pool as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    @Reasoning
    Used only on initialization failure (and from shutdown_thread_pool). Signal
    every already-spawned worker to exit, join their handles, then destroy
    their per-worker arenas. We NEVER abandon a thread handle; joining is
    mandatory to avoid leaking the kernel TID.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    If pool is non-null, set the shutdown_flag via atomic_store_release
    and broadcast on work_cv to wake any worker blocked in
    platform_condvar_wait. Then loop i from 0 to count-1: read the slot
    handle, if non-zero platform_thread_join it and clear the slot, read
    the worker_arena, if non-zero arena_destroy it and clear the slot.
    Order matters: signal first (so workers exit their blocking wait),
    join second (so we know the worker has stopped touching its arena),
    arena_destroy third (so we don't unmap memory the worker is still
    using).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Cleanup is off the hot path - called only at init-failure or end of
    parallel session. The broadcast wakes all waiting workers in one
    syscall (futex_wake with INT_MAX). Each join is one wait4-style
    kernel call; arena_destroy is one munmap. Total cost scales linearly
    with the number of spawned workers but is sub-millisecond for
    typical worker_counts.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    workers_array, count, and pool are compiler-owned. We defensively
    check the pool pointer for 0 before dereferencing because this
    Process is also called from create_worker_threads's roll-back path,
    where a partial pool could be passed. Each slot field is checked
    for non-zero before acting on it (handle != 0 before join,
    worker_arena != 0 before destroy), so re-entering cleanup with an
    already-cleaned slot is safe.
    @End Security_Scope
    :End Note

    If pool is not equal to 0:
        Let shutdown_flag be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with pool, 56
        If shutdown_flag is not equal to 0:
            proc atomic_store_release from Atomic with shutdown_flag, 1
        End If
        Let work_cv be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with pool, 32
        If work_cv is not equal to 0:
            proc platform_condvar_broadcast from Threading with work_cv
        End If
    End If

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let slot_offset be i multiplied by WORKER_SLOT_SIZE
        Let slot be workers_array plus slot_offset
        Let handle be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with slot, 0
        If handle is not equal to 0:
            proc platform_thread_join from Threading with handle
            proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with slot, 0, 0
        End If
        Let worker_arena be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with slot, 16
        If worker_arena is not equal to 0:
            proc arena_destroy from Arena with worker_arena
            proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with slot, 16, 0
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Thread Pool Initialization
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "initialize_thread_pool" that takes main_context as Integer, main_arena as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    @Reasoning
    Build the ThreadPool struct, queue, mutex, two condvars, the completion
    counter, the shutdown flag, then spawn N workers. If
    platform_threading_available() returns 0 we set threading_available=0
    in the pool and return -1 (sentinel: caller falls back to serial).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    All control structures (pool, queue, counter/flag cells, worker slot
    array, worker contexts) live in the main arena. Per-worker arenas are
    created via arena_create (mmap-backed) and destroyed at shutdown. The
    mutex/condvar handles are platform-allocated (futex words on Linux) and
    must be destroyed via platform_mutex_destroy / platform_condvar_destroy.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Worker count is sized from platform_hardware_concurrency at init time,
    capped to a sane upper bound to avoid oversubscription on large hosts.
    The mutex/condvar/counter/flag allocations are one-time, off the hot
    path; the dominant cost is N x arena_create + N x platform_thread_create.
    The pool struct is laid out so the hot fields (work_queue, queue_mutex,
    work_cv, done_cv, completion_counter) sit in a single cache line for
    worker_main's per-iteration reads.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    main_context is the import-system context with its security_flags
    intact; we do not modify those flags. main_arena is the per-compilation
    arena. The platform_threading_available probe gates the entire path: if
    the current backend has not been verified to a known-working state, we
    refuse to spawn workers and return sentinel -1 so the caller falls back
    to serial. This prevents spawning threads on unverified platforms where
    a wrong-platform syscall could corrupt the process.
    @End Security_Scope
    :End Note

    Let existing be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with main_context, 200
    If existing is not equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let available be proc platform_threading_available from Threading
    If available is equal to 0:
        Return -1
    End If

    Let worker_count be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with main_context, 64
    If worker_count is less than or equal to 0:
        Set worker_count to proc platform_hardware_concurrency from Threading
        If worker_count is less than 1:
            Set worker_count to 1
        End If
        proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with main_context, 64, worker_count
    End If

    Let pool be proc arena_allocate from Arena with main_arena, POOL_STRUCT_SIZE
    If pool is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with pool, 0, 0
    proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with pool, 8, worker_count
    proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with pool, 16, 0
    proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with pool, 24, 0
    proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with pool, 32, 0
    proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with pool, 40, 0
    proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with pool, 48, 0
    proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with pool, 56, 0
    proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with pool, 64, 1

    Let work_queue be proc initialize_work_queue with main_arena
    If work_queue is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with pool, 16, work_queue

    Let queue_mutex be proc platform_mutex_create from Threading
    If queue_mutex is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with pool, 24, queue_mutex

    Let work_cv be proc platform_condvar_create from Threading
    If work_cv is equal to 0:
        proc platform_mutex_destroy from Threading with queue_mutex
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with pool, 32, work_cv

    Let done_cv be proc platform_condvar_create from Threading
    If done_cv is equal to 0:
        proc platform_condvar_destroy from Threading with work_cv
        proc platform_mutex_destroy from Threading with queue_mutex
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with pool, 40, done_cv

    Let completion_counter be proc arena_allocate from Arena with main_arena, CELL_SIZE
    If completion_counter is equal to 0:
        proc platform_condvar_destroy from Threading with done_cv
        proc platform_condvar_destroy from Threading with work_cv
        proc platform_mutex_destroy from Threading with queue_mutex
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with completion_counter, 0, 0
    proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with pool, 48, completion_counter

    Let shutdown_flag be proc arena_allocate from Arena with main_arena, CELL_SIZE
    If shutdown_flag is equal to 0:
        proc platform_condvar_destroy from Threading with done_cv
        proc platform_condvar_destroy from Threading with work_cv
        proc platform_mutex_destroy from Threading with queue_mutex
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with shutdown_flag, 0, 0
    proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with pool, 56, shutdown_flag

    proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with main_context, 200, pool
    proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with main_context, 208, work_queue
    proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with main_context, 216, 0

    Let workers_array be proc create_worker_threads with worker_count, pool, main_context, main_arena
    If workers_array is equal to 0:
        proc platform_condvar_destroy from Threading with done_cv
        proc platform_condvar_destroy from Threading with work_cv
        proc platform_mutex_destroy from Threading with queue_mutex
        proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with main_context, 200, 0
        proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with main_context, 208, 0
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with pool, 0, workers_array

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Enqueue / Wait / Shutdown
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "add_import_task" that takes import_path as Integer, enqueue_order as Integer, main_context as Integer, main_arena as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    @Reasoning
    Public producer entry point: build a task, push it onto the queue
    under the mutex, signal one waiting worker. Returns the task pointer
    on success (so process_imports_parallel can index it into the
    tasks_index array for deterministic merge), or 0 on failure.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Look up the pool via main_context offset 200. Read the queue, mutex,
    and work_cv from the pool. Construct the task via create_import_task,
    return 0 if allocation failed. Acquire queue_mutex, enqueue the task,
    release. If enqueue failed (defensive - it cannot under current code
    paths because enqueue resizes on overflow), return 0. Signal work_cv
    so an idle worker wakes up to consume the task.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Mutex hold time is bounded: just one enqueue_task call plus optional
    resize. Signal-after-unlock semantics (we call condvar_signal AFTER
    unlock) avoids the spurious-mutex-reacquire path some monitor
    implementations suffer from. Producers are not on the worker hot
    path; this Process is called once per import on the main thread.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    import_path is a String pointer from the parser's import AST. We do
    not dereference or validate it here - resolve_module_path on the
    worker thread is the security boundary for path validation. The pool
    pointer is read from main_context's known offset 200; if it is 0 we
    return 0 (no enqueue) rather than crashing.
    @End Security_Scope
    :End Note

    Let pool be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with main_context, 200
    If pool is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let work_queue be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with pool, 16
    Let queue_mutex be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with pool, 24
    Let work_cv be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with pool, 32

    Let task be proc create_import_task with import_path, enqueue_order, main_arena
    If task is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc platform_mutex_lock from Threading with queue_mutex
    Let ok be proc enqueue_task with work_queue, task
    proc platform_mutex_unlock from Threading with queue_mutex
    If ok is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc platform_condvar_signal from Threading with work_cv
    Return task
End Process

Process called "wait_for_completion" that takes main_context as Integer, expected_tasks as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    @Reasoning
    Standard monitor wait. We hold queue_mutex (the same mutex workers use
    to publish completion via done_cv) and check the atomic counter under
    that lock. If the counter is short, wait on done_cv; the wait atomically
    releases the mutex and re-acquires it on wakeup, so we cannot miss a
    signal between read and wait.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Look up the pool from main_context offset 200; if 0, treat as
    success (no work to wait for) and return 1. Acquire queue_mutex,
    read the completion counter via atomic_load_acquire, loop while
    it is less than expected_tasks calling platform_condvar_wait then
    re-reading. Release the mutex and return 0 on success.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Spurious wakeups are tolerated by the while-loop predicate
    (completed < expected_tasks), so platform_condvar_wait does not need
    to be perfect. The mutex is held during the wait but condvar_wait
    atomically releases it during the kernel sleep, so workers can
    continue to dequeue and signal done_cv. Wakeup overhead is one futex
    wake per completion, amortized cheap.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    main_context and expected_tasks are compiler-owned. expected_tasks
    is the count of successfully-enqueued imports (returned by
    process_imports_parallel's enqueue loop), so the wait predicate
    cannot overshoot the actual amount of work. If the pool was never
    initialized (offset 200 == 0) we return success without waiting,
    matching the no-work-to-do case.
    @End Security_Scope
    :End Note

    Let pool be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with main_context, 200
    If pool is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let queue_mutex be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with pool, 24
    Let done_cv be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with pool, 40
    Let completion_counter be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with pool, 48

    proc platform_mutex_lock from Threading with queue_mutex
    Let completed be proc atomic_load_acquire from Atomic with completion_counter
    While completed is less than expected_tasks:
        proc platform_condvar_wait from Threading with done_cv, queue_mutex
        Set completed to proc atomic_load_acquire from Atomic with completion_counter
    End While
    proc platform_mutex_unlock from Threading with queue_mutex

    Return 0
End Process

Process called "shutdown_thread_pool" that takes main_context as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    @Reasoning
    Signal shutdown to every worker (atomic store + broadcast on work_cv so
    workers blocked in platform_condvar_wait observe the new shutdown_flag),
    then join every thread handle. Worker arenas are destroyed AFTER the
    merge phase has consumed their AST nodes; we destroy them here, plus
    the platform mutex/condvar handles. Counter/flag cells are arena-owned,
    so they get reclaimed automatically when the import context's arena is
    destroyed at end-of-compilation.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Look up the pool from main_context offset 200; return 0 if not
    initialized. Read workers_array, worker_count, queue_mutex, work_cv,
    done_cv, shutdown_flag. Atomic-release-store 1 into shutdown_flag,
    broadcast work_cv to wake any blocked worker. Two-pass slot loop:
    pass 1 joins every non-zero handle (so we know no worker is still
    touching its arena), pass 2 destroys every non-zero worker_arena.
    Then destroy done_cv, work_cv, queue_mutex (each guarded by non-zero
    check) and clear the pool pointer at context+200 plus the worker
    count at context+208.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Shutdown is one-time per parallel session. The two-pass loop is
    required for correctness (join before arena_destroy); for typical
    worker_counts (4-8) it adds negligible overhead vs a single pass.
    Each thread_join is one wait4-style syscall; each arena_destroy is
    one munmap; each condvar_destroy/mutex_destroy is essentially free
    in the futex implementation.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    main_context is compiler-owned. Every dereferenced field is checked
    for non-zero before use, so partial-init or double-shutdown is safe.
    We clear the pool slot in main_context (offset 200) so subsequent
    calls observe the pool as un-initialized and treat the situation as
    no-op rather than re-running destructors on freed handles.
    @End Security_Scope
    :End Note

    Let pool be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with main_context, 200
    If pool is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let workers_array be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with pool, 0
    Let worker_count be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with pool, 8
    Let queue_mutex be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with pool, 24
    Let work_cv be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with pool, 32
    Let done_cv be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with pool, 40
    Let shutdown_flag be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with pool, 56

    If shutdown_flag is not equal to 0:
        proc atomic_store_release from Atomic with shutdown_flag, 1
    End If
    If work_cv is not equal to 0:
        proc platform_condvar_broadcast from Threading with work_cv
    End If

    If workers_array is not equal to 0:
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than worker_count:
            Let slot_offset be i multiplied by WORKER_SLOT_SIZE
            Let slot be workers_array plus slot_offset
            Let handle be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with slot, 0
            If handle is not equal to 0:
                proc platform_thread_join from Threading with handle
                proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with slot, 0, 0
            End If
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While

        Let j be 0
        While j is less than worker_count:
            Let slot2_offset be j multiplied by WORKER_SLOT_SIZE
            Let slot2 be workers_array plus slot2_offset
            Let warena be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with slot2, 16
            If warena is not equal to 0:
                proc arena_destroy from Arena with warena
                proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with slot2, 16, 0
            End If
            Set j to j plus 1
        End While
    End If

    If done_cv is not equal to 0:
        proc platform_condvar_destroy from Threading with done_cv
        proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with pool, 40, 0
    End If
    If work_cv is not equal to 0:
        proc platform_condvar_destroy from Threading with work_cv
        proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with pool, 32, 0
    End If
    If queue_mutex is not equal to 0:
        proc platform_mutex_destroy from Threading with queue_mutex
        proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with pool, 24, 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with main_context, 200, 0
    proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with main_context, 208, 0

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Result Merge (deterministic, main thread, post-join)
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "merge_worker_results" that takes program as Integer, tasks_array as Integer, import_count as Integer, main_arena as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    @Reasoning
    Run the merge phase on the main thread AFTER every worker has joined.
    Iterate tasks in enqueue_order (= source order) so the merged
    program.functions / program.types arrays are byte-identical to the
    serial path's output. Worker arenas STILL OWN the AST nodes; we copy
    only pointers into main_program. Per design risk in #117 sec5, worker
    arenas must outlive the merge - they do, because shutdown_thread_pool
    destroys them only after this Process returns.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Loop i from 0 to import_count - 1. Read tasks_array[i*8] - if 0 the
    slot has no enqueued task (import statement was empty), skip. Read
    task[32] (error_code); on non-zero, Alert and return 1 (hard fail).
    Read task[24] (parsed_program); if non-zero call
    merge_imported_functions then merge_imported_types from ImportCore
    with (program, parsed_program, main_arena). Each merge returns 0 on
    success; non-zero is a hard fail. Return 0 on full success.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Merge is serial by design (deterministic ordering matters more than
    speed at this step, and per-import merge_imported_functions/types
    each do a fast pointer copy not a deep traversal). Wall time is
    O(total_functions + total_types) across all imports. The pointers
    being copied reference worker-arena memory which remains valid for
    the rest of the compilation pipeline.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    program, tasks_array, and main_arena are compiler-owned. import_count
    is the count from the original program's import statement array. The
    error_code field at task[32] gates the merge: any worker-reported
    failure aborts the merge with diagnostic Alert output rather than
    silently dropping the failed import's data.
    @End Security_Scope
    :End Note

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than import_count:
        Let task_slot_offset be i multiplied by CELL_SIZE
        Let task be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with tasks_array, task_slot_offset
        If task is equal to 0:
            Set i to i plus 1
        Otherwise:
            Let error_code be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with task, 32
            If error_code is not equal to 0:
                Alert "[PARALLEL ERROR] import task failed at index"
                Alert i
                Alert "phase"
                Alert error_code
                Return 1
            End If

            Let parsed_program be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with task, 24
            If parsed_program is not equal to 0:
                Let merge_fn_result be proc merge_imported_functions from ImportCore with program, parsed_program, main_arena
                If merge_fn_result is not equal to 0:
                    Alert "[PARALLEL ERROR] failed to merge functions for task"
                    Alert i
                    Return 1
                End If

                Let merge_ty_result be proc merge_imported_types from ImportCore with program, parsed_program, main_arena
                If merge_ty_result is not equal to 0:
                    Alert "[PARALLEL ERROR] failed to merge types for task"
                    Alert i
                    Return 1
                End If
            End If

            Set i to i plus 1
        End If
    End While

    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Top-Level Entry Point
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "process_imports_parallel" that takes program as Integer, context as Integer, arena as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    @Reasoning
    Orchestrate the full parallel pipeline:
      1. Initialize the pool. If platform_threading_available returns 0,
         immediately return sentinel 2 so the driver falls back to serial.
      2. Allocate a tasks_index array sized to import_count so we can merge
         in deterministic enqueue order after join.
      3. Enqueue every import statement. Workers begin draining as soon as
         the first signal lands.
      4. Wait until completion_counter equals import_count.
      5. Shut down the pool (signal + join + destroy CVs/mutex/per-worker
         arenas).
      6. Merge results into main program on the main thread.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Three-valued return contract: 0 = success, 1 = hard failure, 2 =
    graceful degradation (threading unavailable, caller should fall
    back to serial). Pipeline order: initialize_thread_pool, allocate
    tasks_index (one cell per import for deterministic merge ordering),
    zero-fill the index, walk program.imports (offset 32, count at
    offset 40) calling add_import_task per non-null import and
    recording the resulting task pointer into the index, call
    wait_for_completion with the count of successfully enqueued tasks,
    call merge_worker_results, call shutdown_thread_pool. Diagnostic
    Alert + Return 1 on any allocation, enqueue, wait, or merge failure
    (shutdown is still run in the cleanup-on-failure path to release
    workers).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Speedup is roughly min(N, B) where N = worker_count and B is the
    file-I/O bandwidth divided by mean parse time. For the bootstrap stage1
    self-host we expect 4-8 workers to saturate before B becomes the
    bottleneck. Per-worker arenas eliminate allocator contention; the only
    shared hot path is the queue_mutex which is touched O(import_count)
    times, not O(allocation_count).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    program, context, and arena are compiler-owned. The import statements
    walked from program.imports carry the same security_flags context
    that the serial path uses; per-import path validation happens inside
    process_import_task on the worker via resolve_module_path. The
    sentinel-2 graceful-degradation path is the safety mechanism for
    unverified platforms - it ensures we never spawn threads on a
    platform whose threading primitives have not been verified.
    @End Security_Scope
    :End Note

    Let init_result be proc initialize_thread_pool with context, arena
    If init_result is equal to -1:
        Alert "[PARALLEL UNAVAILABLE] platform threading backend not verified, falling back to serial"
        Return 2
    End If
    If init_result is equal to 0:
        Alert "[PARALLEL ERROR] Failed to initialize thread pool"
        Return 1
    End If

    Let import_count be proc memory_get_dword from MemoryCore with program, 40
    If import_count is equal to 0:
        proc shutdown_thread_pool with context
        Return 0
    End If

    Let imports be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with program, 32
    If imports is equal to 0:
        Alert "[PARALLEL ERROR] No imports array found"
        proc shutdown_thread_pool with context
        Return 1
    End If

    Let tasks_index_bytes be import_count multiplied by CELL_SIZE
    Let tasks_index be proc arena_allocate from Arena with arena, tasks_index_bytes
    If tasks_index is equal to 0:
        Alert "[PARALLEL ERROR] Failed to allocate tasks_index"
        proc shutdown_thread_pool with context
        Return 1
    End If

    Let zero_idx be 0
    While zero_idx is less than tasks_index_bytes:
        proc memory_set_byte from MemoryCore with tasks_index, zero_idx, 0
        Set zero_idx to zero_idx plus 1
    End While

    Let enqueued be 0
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than import_count:
        Let import_offset be i multiplied by CELL_SIZE
        Let import_ptr be imports plus import_offset
        Let import_stmt be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with import_ptr, 0

        If import_stmt is not equal to 0:
            Let import_filename be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with import_stmt, 0
            If import_filename is not equal to 0:
                Let task be proc add_import_task with import_filename, i, context, arena
                If task is equal to 0:
                    Alert "[PARALLEL ERROR] Failed to enqueue task"
                    proc shutdown_thread_pool with context
                    Return 1
                End If
                proc memory_set_qword from MemoryCore with tasks_index, import_offset, task
                Set enqueued to enqueued plus 1
            End If
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Let wait_result be proc wait_for_completion with context, enqueued
    If wait_result is not equal to 0:
        Alert "[PARALLEL ERROR] wait_for_completion failed"
        proc shutdown_thread_pool with context
        Return 1
    End If

    Let merge_result be proc merge_worker_results with program, tasks_index, import_count, arena
    If merge_result is not equal to 0:
        proc shutdown_thread_pool with context
        Return 1
    End If

    proc shutdown_thread_pool with context

    Display "[PARALLEL SUCCESS] Processed "
    Display enqueued
    Display " imports in parallel"

    Return 0
End Process
